erican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Ramon, Ezequiel, Jesus, Santos, Abelino, Alvaro, Angelita, Ascencio, Carmella, Corina, Cosme, Edmundo.","Portuguese (<b>Constâncio</b>) and Spanish: from local equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Constantius</i> (see   Constant  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Constant","meanings":["Medieval form of the Late Latin name <i>Constans</i> ‘steadfast’ (genitive <i>Constantis</i>). This was not a common name in the Middle Ages, but was used particularly in the Maude family. The vernacular variant  <b>Costin</b>  is also found. The name was taken up more widely among Christians from the 17th century onwards, partly because of its transparent meaning and partly as expressing a determination to follow the exhortations of  St Peter : ‘Be sober, be vigilant; because your adversary the devil, as a roaring lion, walketh about, seeking whom he may devour; whom resist stedfast (<i>constant</i>) in the faith’ (1 Peter 5:8–9)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":7,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Constancia de Banastre was born about 1252, in Arborfield, Berkshire, England as the daughter of William de Banastre. She had at least 1 daughter with John de la Hoese II. She died in 1278, in Finchampstead, Berkshire, England, at the age of 27, and was buried in Finchampstead, Berkshire, England."},"et":{"circa 1252–1278":"umbes 1252–1278","1252–1278":"1252–1278","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1277–1333":"1277–1333","1234–Male":"1234–Surnud","1259":"1259","circa 1252":"umbes 1252","1278":"1278","1234":"1234","1333":"1333","1277":"1277","1252":"1252","1240